This article is a press release from the White House Office of the Press Secretary, dated January 27, 2012. It announces an executive order regarding the assignment of functions related to certain promotion and appointment actions in the armed forces. 

According to the order, the Secretary of Defense is assigned to perform the functions of the President under specific provisions of title 10, United States Code. These provisions include reports relating to certain grades, extending officer promotion eligibility periods, and appointments of members of the Marine Band and Marine Drum and Bugle Corps. 

The order also states that the Secretary of Defense may reassign the functions assigned to them, but only to civilian officers within the Office of the Secretary of Defense who hold a position requiring Senate confirmation. However, the function assigned in section 1(c) cannot be reassigned. 

The order includes general provisions clarifying that it does not limit the authority of the President as Commander in Chief or their ability to nominate, make, or terminate appointments. It also states that the order does not create any enforceable rights or benefits against the United States or its entities. The order is signed by President Barack Obama.